 \section spherical_example Spherical scatterer example
 Spherical scatterer example describes a sphere as a scatterer (either soft or rigid), with artificial boundary to be
 convex. And an incident wave is impinging from arbitrary directions on the surface of the scatterer, both total acoustic
 potential and scattering potential filed (pressure) can be calculated from moFEM on the computational domain.
 quantities of Particle velocity and radius stress will be implemented soon.

 \subsection shperical_input_file Input files
 Mesh file with boundary conditions, material properties can be created with Cubit journal file with impinging_sphere.jou,


\code
reset

Set Maximum Arc_Span 30

#The exterior domain can be sphere or cube or any arbitrary convex topology
create sphere radius 3
create sphere radius 0.5
chop volume 1  with volume 2
delete volume 3

set duplicate block elements on

block 1 volume all
block 1 name 'MAT_HELMHOLTZ'
block 1 attribute count 2

#Angular Frequency
block 1 attribute index 1 2
#Sound of speed in medium
block 1 attribute index 2 1

block 3 volume all
block 3 name 'MAT_NORM'
block 3 attribute count 0

#Choose from analytical solution or non-reflection BC
#block 4 surface 3
#block 4 surface all
#block 4 name 'ANALYTICAL_BC'

#ommerfeld BC or B-T 1st BC
block 4 surface 1
#block 4 name 'SOMMERFELD_BC'
block 4 name 'BAYLISS_TURKEL_BC'

#Choose whether the scatterer is sound-soft or sound-hard
block 5 surface 3
#block 5 name 'SOFT_INCIDENT_WAVE_BC'
block 5 name 'HARD_INCIDENT_WAVE_BC'

surface 3 size auto factor 5
mesh surface 3
#surface 8 size auto factor 4
#mesh surface 8

volume all scheme Tetmesh
volume all size auto factor 5
mesh volume all

set duplicate block elements on
block 6 tet all
block 6 element type tetra10
\endcode


